{"timestamp": "2025-12-02 14:01:10.983516", "event": "llm_start", "messages": "content='Based on the diagnosis report: Troubleshooting diagnosis report — network snapshot analysis\\n\\nScope and data used\\n- Inputs: full reachability matrix (ping results) plus targeted pings, host network configs, and FRR routing tables collected from the core routers and the server-access router.\\n- Focus: detect anomalies, localize faulty devices/links, identify likely root causes. No remediation proposed.\\n\\nExecutive summary\\n- Overall OSPF control plane appears converged and healthy: all core routers and the server-access router carry routes to the expected /24 user subnets and the server farm (10.200.0.0/24).\\n- Most hosts can reach the server farm and each other with low latency and no packet loss.\\n- Two distinct anomalies were observed:\\n  1) One access host (host_1_1_1_1) has no IPv4 address and is therefore unreachable.\\n  2) Intermittent packet loss/jitter affecting pings from host_2_2_2_1 to some web servers (web_server_2 and web_server_3) appeared in the reachability matrix; follow-up testing showed the behavior was transient (no sustained loss) but with occasional latency outliers/jitter.\\n\\nDetailed observations and evidence\\n\\n1) Host host_1_1_1_1 — missing IPv4 address, unreachable\\n- In the reachability matrix host_1_1_1_1 appears with null/unknown IP and many \"unknown\" results when other hosts tried to reach it.\\n- Host network config (get_host_net_config for host_1_1_1_1) shows eth0 is UP but there is no inet address assigned:\\n\\n  eth0: flags=4163<UP,BROADCAST,RUNNING,MULTICAST>  mtu 1500\\n  ...\\n  (no \"inet\" line present)\\n\\n- Impact: host_1_1_1_1 cannot participate in IP communications; it will appear offline/unreachable to the rest of the network until an IPv4 address/gateway is assigned.\\n\\nLocalization: failure is local to host_1_1_1_1 (host-level configuration issue).\\n\\nLikely root cause: missing/incorrect IP configuration (no static IPv4 configured and/or DHCP not applied). No evidence in the router routing tables that any network route for host_1_1_1_1 is missing — this is host-side.\\n\\n2) Intermittent packet loss / jitter observed from host_2_2_2_1 to web servers\\n- In the global reachability table, pings from host_2_2_2_1 to:\\n  - web_server_2 (10.200.0.5) reported 50% loss (4 tx, 2 rx).\\n  - web_server_3 (10.200.0.6) reported 25% loss (4 tx, 3 rx).\\n  - Other destinations from the same source (web_server_0, dns_server) showed 0% loss.\\n- Follow-up targeted pings (10 packets) from host_2_2_2_1 show:\\n  - web_server_2: 10/10 received, rtt avg ~4.46 ms, mdev ~2.39 ms, single high outlier (~11.1 ms).\\n  - web_server_3: 10/10 received, rtt avg ~3.29 ms, mdev ~2.50 ms, single high outlier (~10.7 ms).\\n  - web_server_0 and dns_server: 10/10 received, rtt avg in ~3–3.8 ms range, mdev smaller.\\n- Internal server-to-server pings (web_server_1 -> web_server_2/3/0 and among web servers) show 0% loss and low rtt, indicating the server farm internal network is healthy.\\n- FRR routing tables on core routers and on switch_server_access show 10.200.0.0/24 present and advertised, and other user subnets reachable — no missing OSPF routes or clear routing blackholes.\\n\\nLocalization and characterization:\\n- The packet-loss observation was intermittent and not consistently reproducible in the follow-up 10-packet tests. The loss was only seen (in the first matrix) from a single source to particular targets, while other paths from the same source to those targets (or from other sources to the same targets) succeeded.\\n- This pattern localizes the problem to somewhere on the forwarding path between host_2_2_2_1 and the affected web servers (could be an intermediate switch, the distribution/core forward path, or an endpoint temporarily limiting/responding to ICMP).\\n- Because server-to-server pings inside 10.200.0.0/24 are clean and routers carry correct routes, the problem is likely transient packet drop/jitter on the forwarding path rather than a persistent routing convergence issue.\\n\\nPossible root causes (for the observed intermittent loss/jitter)\\n- Transient congestion or CPU scheduling spikes on an intermediate device causing ICMP packet drops and occasional latency spikes.\\n- ICMP rate-limiting (or host-based firewalling) intermittently dropping some ping responses on the server or an intermediate device.\\n- Micro-flap or transient interface errors on a link along the path (but no sustained interface down events appear in router route ages).\\n- Because follow-up extended pings returned 0% loss but with higher mdev and occasional high latency, the issue appears to be short-lived or sporadic rather than a persistent link outage.\\n\\nControl plane / routing state\\n- FRR show ip route outputs from router_core_1, router_core_2, router_core_3, and switch_server_access:\\n  - All core routers advertise and have routes to the user subnets (10.1.x.x and 10.2.x.x) and to 10.200.0.0/24 (server farm).\\n  - The server-access router (switch_server_access) shows 10.200.0.0/24 as directly connected (br0).\\n  - Several OSPF next-hops show equal-cost multipath entries for some infra links (expected in a clustered core topology).\\n- No missing network-level routes were observed; OSPF appears converged with consistent route entries across routers.\\n\\nOther notable items from the reachability matrix\\n- Many cells marked \"unknown\" in the initial matrix were associated with host_1_1_1_1 (which lacks an IP) and with the row for host_2_2_1_1 (host 10.2.2.2) where many destinations returned unknown — that suggests either that particular source had local issues or the reachability checks from that node did not run/complete. A targeted net-config check of host_2_2_1_1 was not performed in this run, so the cause of its many unknown entries is not fully determined here.\\n\\nSummary of findings (concise)\\n- Network control plane (OSPF) converged and healthy; server network reachable from many hosts.\\n- Definitive anomaly: host_1_1_1_1 is reachable at link-layer but has no IPv4 address (host configuration issue) — localized to that host.\\n- Intermittent data-plane anomaly: transient packet loss and latency outliers observed between host_2_2_2_1 and web_server_2/3 (evidence: initial 50%/25% loss in the main matrix, followed by intermittent latency/outliers in extended pings). Localization: forwarding path between that host and server farm (not a routing table absence).\\n- No evidence of persistent routing blackholes or OSPF misconfiguration from the router tables collected.\\n\\nIf you want further diagnostic evidence (I can collect without proposing fixes):\\n- Check host_2_2_1_1 network config and run targeted pings from it to confirm whether its \"unknown\" row was due to its misconfiguration.\\n- Run continuous ping/iperf between host_2_2_2_1 and web_server_2/3 to observe whether packet loss reappears and correlate with interface counters on intermediate routers/switches.\\n- Inspect interface statistics on distribution/core links for errors, drops, or queue drops during the observed events.\\n- Check server-side ICMP/iptables or resource load on web_server_2/3 during the intermittent loss intervals.\\n\\nEnd of report., please provide the submission. Do not submit if no report available.' additional_kwargs={} response_metadata={} id='b6e10dfd-7e23-45f7-8fed-ee9db0b80514'", "model": {"lc": 1, "type": "constructor", "id": ["langchain", "chat_models", "openai", "ChatOpenAI"], "kwargs": {"model_name": "gpt-5-mini", "openai_api_key": {"lc": 1, "type": "secret", "id": ["OPENAI_API_KEY"]}, "stream_usage": true}, "name": "ChatOpenAI"}}
